componentInstanceProperties.value:
How do we make a dent in real-world problems with impact investing? The answer might be as simple as encouraging more people to invest.

If you ask the average person about investing, you may still hear a variety of responses. A  finder survey found that 48% of Australian adults invest and of those, 23% have started investing in the past two years. The vast majority view money in savings accounts as an investment (30%), only 16% invest in specific shares and only 9% in property.

As we head towards February 2023, the overall vibe about the financial markets is perhaps nervous. There is still talk about a recession. There is still a lot of uncertainty about the cost of living and interest rates.

Despite this, investing is gaining momentum amongst a wider range of people, so we are hopeful that the 1 percent shift needed (from regular investing to impact investing) is achievable so we can create change for people and the planet.

Several emerging trends are reshaping the venture capital industry to make wider uptake possible. These include the birth of investment options that democratise access to the market, the transformation of global capital markets in the wake of the global pandemic and other significant issues surrounding automation technology, data and cyber security.

As the world’s economies rebound, there has been an increasing need within the capital markets to shift the paradigm in order to build market resilience, improve ESG governance and retain customer trust. 

So, what are the key emerging trends in wealthtech and how are these likely to impact investing accessibility in the future?

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value:
Emerging wealthtech trends


Here are some of the emerging trends in wealthtech that are likely to influence future investing:

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value: 1. The rise of the retail investor and “meme stocks”

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value:
It is difficult to say with certainty that the emergence of Meme Stocks led to an increase in retail investment, but events like the Gamestop saga definitely signalled the end of professional investor dominance. This trend highlighted the newfound power that retail investors possess in the global investment ecosystem and wealthtech environment. 

Retail investors now make up an estimated 23% of US equity trading volume – more than a two-fold increase since 2010. The rise of new investment platforms such as VentureCrowd have also enabled investing accessibility and now retail investors are challenging the sophisticated investor paradigm as democratisation and digitisation reshape how capital markets operate.

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value: 2. Data and cybersecurity concerns

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value:
Overall, while the digitisation of the capital markets has brought many benefits, such as increased speed, transparency and accessibility, it has also created increased risks. 

One potential concern is the increased speed and scale at which information can be spread and used through digital channels. This can lead to increased market volatility and make it more difficult for regulators to monitor and manage potential risks.

Social media being used to spread misinformation or illegal activities such as insider trading or market manipulation can be more difficult to detect and prevent in a digital environment as well.

In addition, the growing influence of retail investors and the rise of meme stocks have raised concerns about the potential for herd behavior and speculation in the market. This can lead to price bubbles and make the market more vulnerable to sudden price corrections.

Given all the above, it’s no big surprise that data is also now emerging as an asset class of and by itself. Very public cyber security breaches here in Australia in the past year have highlighted the impact of data vulnerabilities. We are also gathering more data than ever before.

Data management infrastructure is a key growth area for traditional financial firms. More and more sectors within the finance industry are seeking ways to integrate Big Data management to keep up with growth and remain competitive and more are also investing in data security to protect businesses and consumers.

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value: 3. The need for greater transparency around ESGs

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value:
Investors are increasingly looking to ESG factors to evaluate companies’ long-term performance and risks, as well as to identify companies that are leaders in sustainability and good corporate citizenship. 

Trust is going to be key in order to drive more people to invest. Given the present-day market uncertainty, significant questions still remain over what market structures and tools are needed to garner trust in the ESG markets and support sustainable investing. 

Improved ESG disclosure provides investors with a more complete picture of a company's performance and risks, including potential reputational, legal, and regulatory risks that may not be fully captured in regular financial reporting.

Greater ESG transparency helps build trust between investors and companies and contributes to the overall integrity and stability of the financial system. It also helps to align the interests of investors and companies with consumers’ growing interest in sustainable development and environmental preservation. 

If we grow a retail investing ecosystem investors can trust, more people will invest and create impact.

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value: 4. The rise of tokenisation

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value:
Despite the events of 2022 (FTX, Luna/Terra etc), crypto and NFTs are here to stay. According to Pitchbook’s 2023 Industry and Technology Outlook, crypto is likely to see an investment resurgence in late 2023, with greater focus on cryptocurrencies that have an underlying utility. 

This is largely thanks to new legislation on the table in the EU and congressional hearings in the US, as well as consumer demand for more transparency.

More regulation will bring with it more market confidence. The EU’s new legislation, the Market in Crypto-assets Regulation (MiCA), is set to be ratified in early 2023 and implemented in early 2024.

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value: 5. Bank/Fintech partnerships

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value:
Older financial institutions are redefining their roles by incorporating fintech or partnering with fintech startups to progress innovation. Fintech firms make it easier to lend money online, threatening traditional bricks and mortar firms as they steal their customers. 

The Economist Impact survey found that just 12% of bankers saw increasing competition from fintech, while almost half reported cooperating with fintech in the past year. With the rise of digitisation, it’s likely to see more banks partnering with fintech startups to make better choices, boost their efficiency and meet consumer demand.

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value: How VentureCrowd’s Vest platform is set to make a difference

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value:
At VentureCrowd we’ve long recognized the power of the crowd, Web3 tokenisation and the need to encourage more people to invest if we are to truly facilitate impact investing.

In 2022, VentureCrowd partnered with venture-focused digital product development firm MakerX to build Vest, a world-first, blockchain-based wealth technology (wealthtech) platform which is set to shock the alternative asset investing system.

Vest will allow syndicate communities to view hyper niche deal flows, invest in deals, and be rewarded for their contributions to the community. 

Funds management functionality via tokenisation will enable security, liquidity and authenticity in trading and lower the barrier of entry for all investors. 

The initiative is seen as a pioneer in the transition to Web3 by bringing together deep technical capabilities, blockchain, UX and design to deliver the next-generation of wealth-tech to the market.

Vest will empower influencers by shifting the power of balance from pro investors to people who have deep domain knowledge. It will also enable more liquidity for startups and investors, meaning the lines between different investment stages will become blurrier, and possibly redundant.

With more high-growth companies staying private for longer, Vest will enable VentureCrowd to position itself as the only capital partners that founders will need from seed to IPO.

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value: The future of wealthtech is the crowd

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value:
Investing as we know it is changing for the better. The wealthtech landscape is rapidly evolving, with more and more people turning to the wealthtech sector to get more out of their assets. 

While the democratisation of public markets is bringing many benefits, it also raises a few challenges to the growing investor pool, including issues surrounding trust and transparency, education and accessibility. 

VentureCrowd is leading the way in our initiative to democratise engagement in the capital markets, giving everyday people access to new wealth creation opportunities in asset classes previously unavailable to them. Platforms like Vest leverage new technology to enable open transparency and allow investors to align with their values and make a difference with their investment. And, our ambitious goal is to enable many more investors to enter the capital markets as impact investors, so we can collectively make the difference we want to in the world.
